{{Infobox language | name = Kyirong | nativename={{lang|ne|स्युबा}} | altname = {{plainlist| * Lende * Kyerung }} | region = [[Tibet]] | speakers = {{sigfig|100|2}} | date = 2002, Ethnologue | ref = | familycolor = Sino-Tibetan | fam2 = [[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] ? | fam3 = [[Bodish languages|Bodish]] | fam4 = [[Tibetic languages|Tibetic]] | fam5 = [[Kyirong–Kagate language|Kyirong–Kagate]] | iso3 = kgy | lc2 = kgy | ld2 = Kyirong | glotto = kyer1238 | glottoname = Kyerung | glottorefname = Kyerung }}'''Kyirong''' is a language from the subgroup of [[Tibetic languages]]<ref name=":122">N. Tournadre (2005) "L'aire linguistique tibétaine et ses divers dialectes." ''Lalies'', 2005, n°25, p.&nbsp;7–56 [http://tournadre.nicolas.free.fr/fichiers/2005-aire.pdf]</ref> spoken in the Kyirung district of the [[Shigatse|Shigatse prefecture]], of the [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibetan Autonomous Region]]. Language structure
Kyirong has [[Tone (linguistics)|lexical tone]], with a three-tone system.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Tibetan dialect of Lende (Kyirong).|last=Huber|first=Brigitte|publisher=VGH Wissenschaftsverlag|year=2005|isbn=|location=Bonn|pages=}}</ref>
== Relationship to other languages == There is a varying degree of mutual intelligibility between Kyirong and other [[Kyirong–Kagate language|Kyirong-Yolmo]] varieties. It is most closely related to the Nubri and Gyalsomdo languages,<ref>{{Cite book|url=|title=An investigation of the relationship between the Kyirong, Yòlmo, and Standard Spoken Tibetan speech varieties (unpublished MA thesis)|last=Hedlin|first=Matthew|publisher=Payap University, Chiang Mai, Thailand|year=2011|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and more distantly related to other languages in the family.<ref name=":13">{{Cite journal|last=Gawne|first=Lauren|date=2013|title=Report on the relationship between Yolmo and Kagate|url=|journal=Himalayan Linguistics|volume=12|pages=1–27|via=}}</ref>
== Phonology ==
=== Consonants === There are 36 consonants in Kyirong, which are summarized in the table below.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable IPA" ! !Bilabial !Apico-Dental !Retroflex !Lamino-post-alveolar !Palatal !Velar !Glottal |- !Voiceless stop |p |t |ʈ | |c |k | |- !Aspirated stop |{{IPA|pʰ}} |{{IPA|tʰ}} |ʈʰ | |cʰ |{{IPA|kʰ}} | |- !Voiced stop |b |d |ɖ | |ɟ |ɡ | |- !Voiceless fricative | |s | |ɕ | | |h |- !Voiced fricative | |z | |ʑ | | |ɦ |- !Voiceless affricate | |ts | |tɕ | | | |- !Aspirative affricate | |tsʰ | |tɕʰ | | | |- !Voiced affricate | |dz | |dʑ | | | |- !Nasal |m |n | | |ɲ |{{IPA|ŋ}} | |- !Voice liquid | |r | | | | | |- !voiced lateral approximant | |l | | | | | |- !unvoiced lateral fricative | |ɬ | | | | | |- !Semivowel |w | | | |j | | |}
=== Vowels === There are eight places of articulation for vowels. There is a length distinction at each place of articulation, as well as a long nasalised vowel.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable IPA" ! !Front I !Front II !Central !Back |- !'''Close''' |i iː iː |y yː yː | |u uː uː |- !Half-close |e eː eː |ø øː øː | |ɔ ɔː ɔː |- !Half-open ! |ɛ ɛː ɛː ! ! |- !Open | | |a aː aː |}
=== Tone === Kyriong has a three tone system; high, medium and low. Low tone is often accompanied by breathy voice.<ref name=":0" />
